<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>/</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Global Justice Center</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The Global Justice Center (GJC) welcomes the opportunity to submit written evidence to the Commons Select Committee on Democracy and Development in Burma. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The GJC is an international human rights organization based in New York that uses legal expertise to shape and leverage international legal precedents in order to dismantle historically patriarchal legal and political structures and replace them with equality-based human rights precepts. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Given the rapidly changing environment in Burma, how should DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">programme</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> develop?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">DFID must demonstrate its commitment to advancing and ensuring equality for the women of Burma by explicitly making women’s empowerment a pillar of its Burma development strategy.  DFID’s Burma program must have as a strategic goal the achievement </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">women’s equality through direct support for women’s empowerment programs that seek to transform power relations within households, markets, communities and national and international economies.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">DFID’s Target Strategy Paper on Gender (the “TSP”) states that “[t]</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> empowerment of women is an essential precondition for the elimination of world poverty and the upholding of human rights…. The purpose of DFID’s strategy is to ensure that women’s empowerment and gender equality are actively pursued in the mainstream of all development activities.”</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The TSP further pledges to support “fundamental changes in</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">policy, laws, and attitudes, while maintaining strategic links with work at the grass roots” and to support interventions focusing on “major policy reforms, changes to laws and regulations, the reallocation of financial and other resources, and the promotion of changes in attitude through public debate.”</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> The TSP identifies 10 specific objectives for gender equality, including reduction of gender-based violence, support for equal participation for women, and increasing livelihood security</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. It also</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> highlights channels through which DFID will support these objectives, including supporting the implementation of the Beijing Platform for Action and fostering collaboration with international institutions.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Pathways of Women’s Empowerment research supported by DFID demonstrates that meaningful interventions must directly focus on women’s political, economic legal empowerment, and on enhancing women’s sexual and reproductive rights.  Pathway’s report states that it is crucial to “include support for women’s </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and other civil society actors to monitor the implementation of policies, and to hold the state and other authorities to account to deliver on their commitments to women.”</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[3]</a></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Despite this powerful rhetoric of policy statements and research in support of women’s empowerment, DFID’s Burma strategy identifies five key pillars, none of which refer to women or women’s empowerment.</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">  DFID must specifically develop a coordinated and explicit gender policy in order to address over 60 years of political, legal and social repression at the hands of the military junta.  DFID must judge its Burma programming against the 10 specific objectives for gender equality that are set forth in the TSP.  Assessing the program against these benchmarks will, we believe, lead to a more coordinated, cohesive strategy.  A limited, piecemeal approach is insufficient to adequately address the deep-rooted inequalities faced by the women of Burma.  </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">For example, DFID’s programming in Burma seeks to improve “local partners’ awareness of the impact their work has on women and girls.”</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Awareness should not be the sum total of civil society support for women but rather one element of a broad, overall coordinated gender empowerment strategy.  DFID must actively support local women’s groups, including by providing funds for coordination and organizational efforts.  DFID’s Pa</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">thway’s study concludes that “</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">[o]</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">rganising</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> is a major route to change and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> a key pathway of empowerment. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Women’s </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and movements are vital in building constituencies for gender justice.”</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Women’s groups need DFID’s assistance to help them develop and implement an overall strategy for women’s equality.  </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Part of DFID’s strategy should be supporting</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the long term structural change that is needed, including constitutional reform and accountability for human rights abuses.  As discussed below, the 2008 Constitution of the Republic of the Union of Myanmar (the “Constitution”), passed by a spurious referendum in 2010, structurally prohibits meaningful participation of Burma’s women in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">the governance of the country. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">DFID’s programs must acknowledge this structural limitation and support in-country women’s groups as they fight for equal rights to participation.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">DFID’s overall strategy must include demands that the government be accountable for achieving human rights benchmarks and</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">meeting international standards.  As one example, President </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Thein</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Sein</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> established by Presidential decree a National Human Rights Commission to promote the fundamental</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> rights of citizens.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> However, the Commission as currently formed does not enjoy a mandate to independently investigate or act upon human rights abuses and is populated by representatives selected solely by the President</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The Commission does not comply with the current international standards as set forth in the Paris Principles</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and the General Observations developed by the International Coordinating Committee of National Human Rights Institutions.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The United Kingdom and other donor countries must ensure that the Commission not be a token mouthpiece of the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">xecutive </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ranch and that it meets international human rights standards.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Given the extraordinary opportunity Burma has to move towards democracy, is DFID’s </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">programme</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> giving sufficient attention to assisting this process? </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">One of DFID’s strategic “pillars” in Burma is to strengthen the work of Parliament.</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">  However, no amount of democratic governance </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">development programming can overcome the structural challenges faced by Parliament as a result of the Constitution.  As </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Daw</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Aung</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> San </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Suu</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Kyi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> bluntly stated:</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">“This Constitution is anti-democratic</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">”</span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The Constitution presents numerous and significant structural barriers to democracy including: placing the military outside the control of the sovereign government,</span><a name="_ednref9"></a><a href="#_edn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> granting the military complete immunity for its actions,</span><a name="_ednref10"></a><a href="#_edn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> ensuring that 25% of Parliamentarians are hand-picked by the military thus ensuring a veto </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">power </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> on</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> constitutional </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">amendments,</span><a name="_ednref11"></a><a href="#_edn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> restricting who can be elected President,</span><a name="_ednref12"></a><a href="#_edn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and establishing “gender apartheid” through provisions designed to limit women’s political power.</span><a name="_ednref13"></a><a href="#_edn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">  It is crucial that DFID and the international community vocally and vigorously support </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Daw</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Aung</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> San </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Suu</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Kyi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> and other democracy activists who are struggling to amend the Constitution.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">DFID policy must also ensure that true democracy can take hold in Burma by supporting judicial reform.  The Constitution does not give the judiciary independence from the executive branch and allows all military matters to be tried solely by the military.</span><a name="_ednref14"></a><a href="#_edn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">  An independent judiciary is a fundamental requirement of democracy as it provides an indispensable check on other branches of the government thereby protecting against violations of citizen’s rights.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Are DFID’s plans to strengthen the work of Burma’s parliament adequate? Should DFID be doing more in this area?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Data compiled by the Inter-Parliamentary Union shows that Burma has extremely low levels of participation by women in parliamentary structures, with women holding 4 out of the 224 seats (1.8%) in the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Amoyotha</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hluttaw</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and 26 out of 431 seats (6%) in the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Pyithu</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hluttaw</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ednref15"></a><a href="#_edn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">While the Gender Annex to DFID’s Burma Operational Plan recognizes that participation in Parliament is “minimal”, the Gender Annex does not set forth any work to improve women’s political participation beyond “increased representation in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">local</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> decision making bodies” (emphasis added). </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Women’s voices must be heard as a collective political bloc and women’s political influence must be proportionate to their numbers in the population. In Burma, over sixty years of military rule has reinforced and perpetuated discrimination against women by preventing them from achieving positions of political power.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">he 2008 Constitution requires that the Defense Services appoint 25% of parliamentarians and guarantees that the Defense Forces will remain the integral and dominant political force of Burma.  Because women are not admitted to the Defense Services (</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Tatmadaw</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">), women have been ineligible for the employment, education, business, joint venture and travel opportunities created by military status. Women have been unable to participate in formal governing structures throughout Burmese history, and the Constitution formally legalizes women’s disengagement from the political process.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Burma is a party to the Convention on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women (“CEDAW”). Article 7 of CEDAW secures women’s rights to participate in political and public life through voting, government service, holding public office, and formulating policy.  In the CEDAW Committee’s General Comment 23, it is suggested that countries implement gender neutral quotas requiring that neither sex constitute less than 40% of a public body, quotas for women in public office, and rules giving preference to women nominees.</span><a name="_ednref16"></a><a href="#_edn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">  The Committee also notes that “research demonstrates that if women’s participation reaches 30 to 35 percent (generally termed a ‘critical mass’), there is a real impact on political style and the content of decisions, and political life is revitalized.”</span><a name="_ednref17"></a><a href="#_edn17">[17]</a></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">In her March 2013 speech on how UK aid will support girls and women’</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s rights, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Development Secretary Justine Greening stated that</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> “Research clearly demonstrates that women’s political participation achieves real changes – in policy choices and in social and political institutions.”</span><a name="_ednref18"></a><a href="#_edn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">This should be a key component of DFID’s work to strengthen Burma’s parliament. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Key to achieving the goal of women’s equal participation in </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">arliament is the repeal of structural barriers to participation, including constitutional provisions</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">DFID must support such measures that</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> ha</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> also been identified as essential by civil society groups on the ground. Furthermore, DFID should focus on improving the levels of women’s participation in decision making bodies at all levels. Such efforts can help support processes to pass and implement legislation or temporary special measures that create gender quotas. Furthermore, DFID should support efforts</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> build leadership skills and women’s capacity to participate in decision making bodies, including the national parliament.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What role should DFID play in helping to resolve ethnic tensions?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Security Council Resolution 1325 requires women’s participation</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> in peace processes, recognizing it as key to building sustainable peace. The UK’s National Action Plan on UNSCR 1325 (“NAP”) explicitly recognizes that participation is one of the four major pillars of the Security Council’s women, peace and security series. However, while the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Gender Annex to DFID’s Burma operational plan clearly recognizes the impact of over si</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">x decades of conflict in Burma, it does not incorporate these mandates of the women, peace and security series into its response.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Currently </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">there is </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">minimal participation by women as a part of any of Burma’s numerous negotiations for peace. A report by the Swedish Burma Committee found that, “</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">…women in Burma are effectively excluded from participating in the negotiations for peace. Less than a handful of</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> women have been part of the offi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">cial talks held between the State and the armed groups, and no</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ne of the 12 preliminary cease fi</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">re agreements reviewed for this report includes any references to gender or women.”</span><a name="_ednref19"></a><a href="#_edn19">[19]</a></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">DFID should ensure that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> funding of any part of Burma’s peace process and resolution of ethnic tensions complies with the international legal requirements of Security Council Resolution 1325 and other resolutions on women, peace and security. </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">This should include demands of milestones and markers from groups funded by DFID, such as the Myanmar </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Peace Center</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">, in ensuring that women are present at the table. Furthermore, DFID funding for such processes should earmark specific funding which aims to increase women’s participation in delegations, including by supporting access by civil society groups, in particular women’s groups, in peace talks. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">The conflict in Burma has also been characterized by rampant human rights abuses, including sexual violence, and resolution of the conflict must include post-conflict justice </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">and reparations </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">processes for these crimes. However, in Burma a key barrier to such processes i</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the constitutional amnesty guaranteed to the Burmese military for war crimes, including sexual violence.</span><a name="_ednref20"></a><a href="#_edn20">[20]</a></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Such an amnesty is contrary to international law</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> Security Council Resolutions and the UN</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">explicitly</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">“does not recognize any amnesty for genocide, crimes against humanity, war crimes, and other serious violations of international humanitarian law.”</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, both the G-8 Declaration on Preventing Sexual Violence in Conflict and the GA Declaration of Commitment to End Sexual Violence in Conflict, which were spearheaded by Foreign Minister Hague, explicitly reject suc</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">h amnesties. The GA declaration</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> call</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">s on all states that </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">sign the pledge to “</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">ensure that all peace, security and conflict mediation processes explicitly </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">recognise</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> the need to prevent, respond to and reduce crimes of sexual violence in conflict and</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">stressed the need to exclude such crimes from amnesty</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">provisions.”</span><a name="_ednref21"></a><a href="#_edn21">[21]</a></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">Any engagement by DFID in peace processes must demand that no such amnesties are included as a part of the process on both sides. Furthermore, and more importantly, since the 2008 Constitution contains a permanent amnesty for the Burmese military for any such crimes, DFID must engage in constitutional reform efforts that support repeal of this provision which violates international law and UK policy.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively is DFID working with the FCO and other UK Government Departments, and how might this improve?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">DFID should strengthen its work with FCO on two key aspects of its programmatic work in Burma. First, DFID should more clearly incorporate the FCO’s UK NAP on women, peace and security, into its work on Burma, in particular with respect to conflict resolution and post-conflict processes (see </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">paras</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. 17-19 above). Second, DFID should also strengthen its relationship with the ongoing work of the FCO’s Preventing Sexual Violence in Conflict Initiative (PSVI) (see </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">paras</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">. 20-22 above). </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn1"></a><a href="#_ednref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">“Poverty elimination and the empowerment of women; strategies for achieving the international development targets” DFID, Sept. 2000, at 8-9 [hereafter, “TSP”].</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn2"></a><a href="#_ednref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">TSP, at 8.</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_edn3"></a><a href="#_ednref3">[3]</a><span sty